  "market_context": "ETH was in a continuous downtrend, then swept the previous day low and produced a bullish closure through down-close candles on the higher timeframe, signaling a potential reversal back into the prior range.",
  "key_observation": "On the 5-minute, price retested the change in state of delivery into a fair value gap and formed the reversal wick prior to the new hourly candle opening, leaving the invalidation level very close to the open price.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify higher-timeframe context — continuous downtrend with a sweep of previous day low and a bullish closure through the down-close candles.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the 5-minute timeframe to seek confirmation: closure through the series of down-close candles into the important level (change in state of delivery + fair value gap).",
    "Step 3: Note that on the 5-minute, price retested the CISD into the FVG and the reversal wick (invalidation) had already formed before the new hourly candle opened.",
    "Step 4: Because invalidation sits very close to the opening price (0.5 of the wick respected), prepare to enter on the open of the new hourly candle.",
    "Step 5: Drop to the 1-minute timeframe — inversion is already present going into the open, with the t-spot forming right at that level.",
    "Step 6: Enter on the open using the inversion, with stop placed on the low of the wick, expecting a shallow wick and expansion higher."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade worked — price made a shallow wick, did not return below the low, and expanded higher as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "When the reversal wick (invalidation) forms prior to the new hourly candle open and sits close to the opening price, the inversion can be entered directly on the open with tight risk, expecting shallow wick formation and immediate expansion.",
